To find the last number that Bella will name before falling asleep, we can iterate through the multiples of N until we have seen all ten digits (0-9) at least once. Here's a C# code that solves the problem:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        int N = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

        if (N == 0)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("INSOMNIA");
        }
        else
        {
            int count = 0;
            int[] digits = new int[10];

            while (count < 10)
            {
                for (int i = 1; i <= 1000000; i++)
                {
                    int number = N * i;
                    UpdateDigits(number, digits);
                }

                count = CountDigits(digits);
                N++;
            }

            Console.WriteLine(N - 1);
        }
    }

    static void UpdateDigits(int number, int[] digits)
    {
        while (number > 0)
        {
            int digit = number % 10;
            digits[digit] = 1;
            number /= 10;
        }
    }

    static int CountDigits(int[] digits)
    {
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < digits.Length; i++)
        {
            count += digits[i];
        }

        return count;
    }
}
```

The code reads the input integer N and handles the case when N is 0 by printing "INSOMNIA" and exiting. Otherwise, it initializes a count variable to keep track of the number of unique digits seen and creates an array called digits to mark which digits have been seen (0-9).

The code then enters a while loop that continues until count reaches 10 (indicating that all digits have been seen). In each iteration of the loop, we use a for loop to iterate through a large range of numbers (in this case, up to 1,000,000). We multiply N by the current iteration number and update the digits array using the UpdateDigits method, which extracts each digit from the number and marks it as seen in the digits array.

After the for loop, we check the current count of unique digits using the CountDigits method. If count is still less than 10, we increment N and continue to the next iteration of the while loop. Once count reaches 10, we subtract 1 from N and print it as the last number before falling asleep.

